nodes.bodyText:
I'm a little confused by this class.  Why does it have all this code to convert to and from a string representation in the form <state>: <count>, <state>: <count>?  Why not just return this as a JSON Object?  The Jackson does all the heavy lifting for you!
 {
     "CREATED": 1,
     "RUNNING": 2
}
This can be achieved with:
@JsonIgnoreProperties(ignoreUnknown = true)
public class KafkaStreamsStateCount {

  private final Map<State, Integer> states;

  public KafkaStreamsStateCount() {
    this.states = new HashMap<>();
  }

  @SuppressWarnings("unused") // Invoked by reflection
  @JsonCreator
  public KafkaStreamsStateCount(final Map<State, Integer> states) {
    this.states = new HashMap<>(states);
  }

  public void updateStateCount(final String state, final int change) {
    updateStateCount(KafkaStreams.State.valueOf(state), change);
  }

  public void updateStateCount(final KafkaStreams.State state, final int change) {
    states.compute(state, (key, existing) ->
        existing == null
            ? change
            : existing + change
    );
  }

  @JsonValue
  public Map<KafkaStreams.State, Integer> getState() {
    return states;
  }

  @Override
  public boolean equals(final Object o) {
    if (this == o) {
      return true;
    }

    if (o == null || getClass() != o.getClass()) {
      return false;
    }

    final KafkaStreamsStateCount that = (KafkaStreamsStateCount) o;
    return Objects.equals(states, that.states);
  }

  @Override
  public int hashCode() {
    return Objects.hash(states);
  }
}

